Another division of res publicae is into res in patrimonio populi and res non in patrimonio populi. Under the former aro included the public treasury, the public domain, public slaves, boqueats lapsing to the state (caduca) or res privatae otherwise devolving on the state ; in other words, all things of which the state as universitas

retains not only the property but also the use and disposition (res .

enim fiscales quasi propriae et privatae principis sunt, Dig. 43, 8, 2, 4). The other class includes high reads, public rivers, public buildings, dre, thetis, all things of which the property is in the community and theuso in the members of the community. Or we may say that the property is in the universitas, but it is subject to a personal servitude (usus) vested in all the private members of that universitas (singuli, universi).

Not only res publicae but res privatae may be thus subject. For instance, the banks ol public rivers and the trees thereupon are the property os the adjacent proprietors; but the navigatore of these rivers have the right ol mooring, lending, unleding, and using the banks in various other ways, Inst. 2, l, 4.
